==French==

===Etymology===
From the prefix ''[[tri-]]'', meaning ''three'' + ''[[-illion]]'' (from [[million]]); [[i.e.]] a [[million]] [[million]] [[million]].

Coined by [[w:Jehan Adam|Jehan Adam]] in 1475 as '''trimillion'''.<ref name="genevieve" /> <ref name="parchemin" /> <ref name="thorndike" />
Rendered as '''tryllion''' by [[w:Nicolas Chuquet|Nicolas Chuquet]] in 1484, in his article “Triparty en la science des nombres”.<ref name="Chuquet1" /> <ref name="Chuquet2" />

===Cardinal number===
'''trillion'''

# A [[w:Long and short scales|long scale]] [[trillion#English|trillion]], 10<sup>18</sup>; a [[w:Long and short scales|short scale]] [[quintillion]].

====Related terms====
* [[billion]], coined at same time

====Descendants====
* Catalan: {{l|ca|trilió}}

